All aboard! 🚊 The cultural heart of Glacier National Park, Rogers Pass NHS Mount Revelstoke and Glacier national parks, offers a unique history of the Canadian Pacific Railway Company, and is a beautiful spot to explore for those who ❤️ to ski. 

But wait… Make sure not to forget your Winter Permit! #DYK? Glacier National Park is home to the world’s largest mobile avalanche control program! Together with the Canadian Armed Forces, Parks Canada conducts avalanche control with artillery to ensure safety of transportation throughout the park, resulting in daily openings and closures. In order to ski in this area, visitors must take part in the Winter Permit System. Learn more about how you can get your permit here: http://ow.ly/Vmnu30gV6eW

To celebrate #Canada150, we're featuring ALL of our 200+ places across our social media accounts. Stay tuned!

caption_original: In approximately 30 locations across Ivvavik National Park, Parks Canada installs weatherproof motion-triggered wildlife cameras. Resource Conservation Officers primarily use this data to monitor grizzly bear activity in the park, especially during the caribou migration, and to learn what other animals may be active in the area.

caption_original:
The Canadian Coast Guard, the Royal Canadian Mounted Police and Canadian Pacific Railway paid homage to a true Canadian hero with the unveiling of a commemorative plaque aboard the Canadian Coast Guard Ship Private Robertson V.C. in Burlington Ontario December 10 2017.

Private James Peter Robertson was awarded posthumously the Victoria Cross for his extraordinary valour and devotion to duty while facing a hostile force in one of the most significant battles in World War I, at Passchendaele Belgium.

CP commissioned the plaque at the request of CP engineer Darrel Sundholm of Calgary Alberta. “After his family moved from Springhill Nova Scotia to Medicine Hat Alberta, James Peter Robertson joined the Canadian Pacific Railway, working his way up to locomotive engineer. He earned his nickname “Singing Pete” for his cheerful singing and whistling, whether in the cab or at the roundhouse,” said Sundholm. “The bravery that earned him the Victoria Cross made him a legend among locomotive engineers the world over.”

Steve Pauley, Commanding Officer of the Canadian Coast Guard ship named in Robertson's honour stated at the ceremony “In this, the 100th year anniversary of his death, it is our honour to share the story of Private Robertson’s service to our country and remember his ultimate sacrifice with dignity and respect.” Pauley added “This plaque will educate all who step aboard this ship for many years to come.”

CP commissioned the plaque at the request of CP engineer Darrel Sundholm of Calgary Alberta. “After his family moved from Springhill Nova Scotia to Medicine Hat Alberta, James Peter Robertson joined the Canadian Pacific Railway, working his way up to locomotive engineer. He earned his nickname “Singing Pete” for his cheerful singing and whistling, whether in the cab or at the roundhouse,” said Sundholm. “The bravery that earned him the Victoria Cross made him a legend among locomotive engineers the world over.” Steve Pauley, Commanding Officer of the Canadian Coast Guard ship named in Robertson's honour stated at the ceremony “In this, the th year anniversary of his death, it is our honour to share the story of Private Robertson’s service to our country and remember his ultimate sacrifice with dignity and respect.” Pauley added “This plaque will educate all who step aboard this ship for many years to come.”

caption_original: Guess what? We built two “supersites” in Iqaluit and Whitehorse! A supersite has a variety of weather instruments that allow scientists to measure atmospheric conditions in detail. For people living in the North, information like the temperature and humidity isn’t as important as they are in the South. Knowing about blowing snow and ice-fog (a fog made up of small ice crystals suspended in the air!) are much more relevant! The new sites will help us understand what weather instruments will work best, so that we can improve weather forecasts in the North....

caption_original: The Round Goby is a small, bottom-dwelling invasive fish that has unfortunately spread through all five Great Lakes in less than a decade. To prevent the spread of this invasive species, never buy or use Round Goby as bait, and never live transfer bait between waterbodies, which are against the law. They prefer waters with rocky and sandy bottoms, and feed aggressively on insects, molluscs, and other small organisms. They have even been known to eat juvenile freshwater mussels, many of which are at-risk! Round Goby are also found in some inland waters in southern Ontario such as Lake Simcoe, the Trent River, Rice Lake, and parts of the Otonabee River. To report sightings, please visit http://ow.ly/VBIh30gZZE2

This past summer, an underwater cable system was laid in part of the Northwest Passage to help scientists measure ice thickness, water temperature, passive acoustics & much more. This system helps to collect important data in real-time, even when the ice is 4m thick! http://ow.ly/QX4V30hnL1f

For the SIXTH day of our 12 day holiday countdown ☃️… here are SIX Coast Guard employees who have served with the Canadian Armed Forces.

Rick Fougère, Incident Command Syst. Officer, retired from the Canadian Forces after 25 years of service and transferred to the Coast Guard.

Evan Boettger, Project Director, enrolled in the Canadian Forces as a Reservist in 1976 and served until his retirement from the Royal Canadian Navy in 2015.

Rob Justice joined the Coast Guard in 2013 following a lengthy career in the Royal Canadian Navy. He is now Manager, Office of Incident Management in Ottawa.

Eric Arsenault retired from the Canadian Forces after 20 years of service and is now a National Project Manager with us.

Lieutenant-Commander Sheyla Dussault, Manager of Search and rescue, joined the Naval Reserve in 1993 and she is still serving today.

caption_original:
Did you know that two science weather supersites have been built in Iqaluit and Whitehorse? The weather information required in the North differs from what the population uses in the rest of Canada. For example, blowing snow and ice-fog are critical information for northern communities; more relevant than the temperature and humidity. 

Environment and Climate Change Canada’s Weather Science team will use the data from the supersites to better understand and support weather forecasts that are more relevant to the needs of the people living in the North. #ArcticScience

caption_original: Our scientists in Newfoundland and Labrador are improving the accuracy of weather and climate forecasts for all Canadians through important contributions to ocean forecasting systems. Over the past two years, researchers like Fraser Davidson have deployed 50 oceanographic ‘drifters’ to collect hourly data on temperature and air pressure on the Newfoundland and Labrador Shelves. This data allows us to work with Environment and Climate Change Canada to evaluate and improve marine weather forecasting systems. This map shows a day’s estimated currents with tracks of all drifters deployed in the area over the last 18 months. http://navigator.oceansdata.ca/

caption_original:
Have you ever wondered where the salmon in British Columbia’s hatcheries come from? First, we capture adult salmon to collect their milt and eggs, which are mixed together to fertilize and then placed in an aquarium to incubate. Once the eggs have hatched, the young salmon are fed in rearing ponds until they’re ready to be released into local streams. These practices allow our hatcheries to follow the natural life cycle of salmon while they work to improve low salmon stocks.  
Learn more about the Pacific salmon life-cycle here: http://ow.ly/wR1k30himnz

caption_original:
On December 5, Canada became the first country to sign a Technical Arrangement for Maintenance with Japan.  This means that each country:
• Accepts the aircraft and equipment maintenance safety standards of the other
• No longer needs to conduct double inspections
• Will reduce industry costs
• Will see growth in their aviation industries
Robert Sincennes, of Transport Canada Civil Aviation, and Mitsuo Kawakami, of the Japan Civil Aviation Bureau of the Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism, signed the agreement at Transport Canada headquarters in Ottawa.  It will come into effect in February 2018.

Don’t forget to put out the fire before Santa comes down the chimney! 

And if you’re buying firewood, make sure it’s sold on the basis of a legal unit of measurement such as a stacked cubic metre. Be present at delivery and get a receipt, then neatly stack and measure your unloaded firewood.

SAFETY NOTICE: Watson Lake, Yukon
Transport Canada is doing work on the ice surface of Watson Lake, Yukon near the Watson Lake Airport. From December 2017 to January 2018, small sections of the ice will be open to allow access to the lake bed. Open water near the airport will be clearly marked with fencing until the work is done, and the lake has safely frozen over. Be very careful in this area.
This work is part of Transport Canada’s efforts to remove contamination from past commercial and military activities that were not understood as harmful at the time.
To learn more, please contact Holly Poklitar, Environmental Officer, Transport Canada at 204-688-3872.

Today, Minister Jim Carr of Natural Resources Canada announced the creation of a Generation Energy Council to provide recommendations on how Canada can prepare for the reliable, affordable, low-carbon economy of the future. 

The Council will assemble takeaways from both the #GenEnergy forum and the six-month engagement that asked Canadians from across the country what their energy future looked like. 

Transforming how our society makes, moves and uses energy will redefine Canada’s energy future, resulting in good, middle-class jobs and a sustainable environment for future generations.

Learn more: http://ow.ly/C0EN30hbjsO

caption_original:
The Tubenose Goby is a small, bottom-dwelling invasive fish that lives among the aquatic vegetation found in nearshore waters of lakes and rivers. Since its discovery in North America in the late 1980s, Tubenose Goby have been found in a few locations in the Great Lakes. To prevent the spread of this invasive species, never buy or use Tubenose Goby as bait, and never transfer live bait between waterbodies. It is against the law. Scientists are concerned about the possible long-term effects, because it can beat resident fish for habitat and food. This is a real concern for bottom-dwelling fishes, like Rainbow Darter and Northern Madtom.
For more information, or to report sightings, please visit http://ow.ly/KiLk30h9x2w

Air pollution is one of the most significant environmental problems affecting our health. It adversely affects our lakes and oceans, and causes acid rain and smog. Some of the air pollution in Canada comes from outside the country. That’s why Canada just ratified the Gothenburg Protocol, an international agreement to reduce air pollutants. 

Under the Protocol, Canada will continue taking action on air pollution by reducing these dangerous emissions. 

We’re taking action to provide Canadians with clean air and a healthier environment.

caption_original:
Interested in knowing how we determine the "suitability" of a foreign ship to perform a proposed marine activity?

Three steps: 
1. We look at its technical and operational characteristics.
2. We look at the commercial and economic implications of using the foreign ship versus the offered Canadian ship.
3. We need you to convince us that a foreign ship is "suitable" from a commercial point of view.

For more information, see section 3.4.2 of our Guidelines at http://ow.ly/k3Xp30aF1t8.

caption_original:
CN and CP exceed their Maximum Grain Revenue Entitlements for Crop Year 2016-2017

The Canadian Transportation Agency (CTA) ruled that revenues of the Canadian National Railway Company (CN) and the Canadian Pacific Railway Company (CP) have exceeded their Maximum grain revenue entitlements for crop year 2016-2017.

- CN’s grain revenue of $808,213,784 was $5,773,741 above its entitlement of $802,440,043.
- CP's grain revenue of $725,457,448 was $1,078, 947 above its entitlement of $724,378,501.

CN and CP now have 30 days to pay the amount by which they exceeded their 2016-2017 revenue entitlements, in addition to a five percent penalty of $288,687 for CN and $53,947 for CP. Regulations stipulate that such payments must be made to the Western Grains Research Foundation, a farmer-financed and directed organization set up to fund research that benefits Prairie farmers.
In the 2016-2017 crop year, 43,196,615 tonnes of Western grain were moved—6.9 percent more than the volume moved during the previous crop year. The average length of haul of 953 miles was two miles, or 0.2 percent, higher than the previous crop year.

http://ow.ly/xWfM30hm73P
